The paper discusses the h-index, which is a metric commonly used in the field of computer science to evaluate the impact of researchers. The study analyzes the evolution of the timed h-index, which is a modification of the h-index that restricts the evaluation to a publication and citation time window. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), cybernetics (cs.CY), social and information networks (cs.SI), and cryptography and security (cs.CR). However, given that the study focuses on bibliometric analysis, cs.DL and cs.IR are the most likely sub-categories.
